title: Symbolic dimensions are not replaced with 1
body:
**Describe the bug**
[This piece of code](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/48f69cfbb8effe30ece62f03504a99a92d5759a7/onnxruntime/python/tools/onnxruntime_test.py#L54):
```
        # replace any symbolic dimensions (value is None) with 1
        shape = [dim if dim else 1 for dim in input_meta.shape]
```
doesn't work as expected.

When `dim` is a string (not `None`), that string is added to `shape` (not `1`), which blows up `size=tuple(shape)` later:
```
        if input_meta.type in float_dict:
            feeds[input_meta.name] = np.random.rand(*shape).astype(float_dict[input_meta.type])
        elif input_meta.type in integer_dict:
            feeds[input_meta.name] = np.random.uniform(high=1000,
                                                       size=tuple(shape)).astype(integer_dict[input_meta.type])
```

**Urgency**
None. Found a workaround (see below).

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Ubuntu 18.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary
- ONNX Runtime version: GPU nightly 4/25
```
$ pip install --index-url https://test.pypi.org/simple/ ort-gpu-nightly --user
```
- Python version: 3.6.10
- Visual Studio version (if applicable): N/A
- GCC/Compiler version (if compiling from source): N/A
- CUDA/cuDNN version: N/A
- GPU model and memory: N/A

**To Reproduce**
Sorry, can't recall exactly what I was doing, but it was with `onnxruntime_test --profile`.

**Expected behavior**
`shape` should only contain integers.

**Screenshots**
N/A

**Additional context**
I've fixed it locally as follows:
```
53    for input_meta in sess.get_inputs():
54        # replace any symbolic dimensions (value is None) with 1
55        shape = [dim if type(dim)==int else 1 for dim in input_meta.shape]
```

title: [Node.js binding] add build flag for node.js binding
body:
**Description**: add build flag for node.js binding. Now the main build script can build Node.js binding by specifying flag `--build_nodejs`. 

Building onnxruntime Node.js binding depends on custom steps that utilizes Node and NPM:
```
npm ci --ort-skip
npm run build
npm test
```

`npm ci` is "clean install" that pulls dependencies node modules and run custom installing script. `--ort-skip` is a flag to skip running building in installation stage (which will be run explicitly in the next command). This command will build typescript code (`tsc`).

`npm run build` runs binding's custom building script, which calls **cmake-js** to build binding.

`npm test` will run unittest and some E2E tests to make sure the binding is working.

title: Fix C# layer in the way it handles sequences
body:
**Description**: 

Originally wanted to fix https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/3181, but the fix for it was checked-in as part of https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/3171, and hence added a test case to keep it covered. While adding the test case, I realized that the C# layer was releasing the native OrtValue for each element in a sequence tensor. This is okay for a sequence of maps but if it were a sequence of tensors, releasing the OrtValue will mean that underlying native memory holding the tensor data is possibly lost before use by the caller. This change fixes that and adds a test case that keeps this and the bug fix for #3181 covered. 

**Motivation and Context**
#3181

title: Expected storage order for Ort tensors

labels.name: stale
labels.description: issues that have not been addressed in a while; categorized by a bot

body:
I am using the C++ API. When calling `ort::Value::CreateTensor` to wrap a data blob that is allocated and owned by another framework (OpenCV for example), what storage order does ORT expect? Row major or column major?

Is ORT implemented in a way that storage order does not even matter when passing data to `Run()`?

I cannot find any documentation that clarifies this question.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution: Linux Ubuntu 18.04
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.2.0
- Python version: 3.6

**Additional context**
I would like to pre-process images with opencv and then run inference with ORT directly without using OpenCV’s built-in support for ONNX models. This means converting a cv::Mat to an Ort Tensor. The following issue suggests that ORT expects row major order in all data blobs (opencv stores data in row major order).

title: Fix a couple of subgraph related edges cases
body:
**Description**: 
2 edge cases as described here: https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/issues/3755#issuecomment-631237586

1. Create a NodeArg for subgraph inputs even if they have no type. If they are only used as an implicit input to another level of nested subgraph we will not create a NodeArg via any other path

2. Allow an If output to have no shape. Obscure edge case where a loop carried dependency to a Loop node is passed through a nested If node subgraph (i.e. the Loop subgraph contains an If node with a nested subgraph for the else_branch/then_branch). We can't infer a shape for a loop carried dependency (they may change across iterations), which means we can't infer a shape for the nested If subgraph output either. We have delayed allocation support for If outputs so use that.

**Motivation and Context**
#3755

```
from detectron2.data.transforms as T #just for resize
filelist = os.listdir('./')
sess = onnxruntime.InferenceSession('./segmentation.onnx')
for i in filelist:
    inputs = cv2.imread('./' + i)
    transform_gen = T.ResizeShortestEdge([800,800],1333)
    inputs = transform_gen.get_transform(inputs).apply_image(inputs)
    inputs = torch.as_tensor(inputs.astype('float32').transpose(2,0,1))
    inputs = inputs.unsqueeze(0)
    res = sess.run(None, {sess.get_inputs()[0].name:inputs.numpy()})
    print (res)
```

title: Use cached io for model loading
body:
**Description**: 

Our Azure build VM has a IOPS cap of 500, which is far less a physical SSD can do.  
https://azure.microsoft.com/en-us/pricing/details/managed-disks/

A real SSD can do 100k-500k random reads per second!
https://www.intel.com/content/dam/www/public/us/en/documents/product-specifications/ssd-750-spec.pdf

As long as you're not limited to IOPS,  the old implementation(zero copy without cache) is good, it can increase the perf up to 50%. However, if it's virtual machine, things could be totally different. 


**Motivation and Context**
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here.
